    <div class="content-section" id="overview">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Overview</div>
      <div class="section-title">Who do you come from?</div>
      <p>Students design a trading card featuring a personal hero — a family member, community figure, historical person, or anyone who has shaped who they are. This unit introduces colored pencil as a medium and color theory as a formal discipline, while staying rooted in the personal. The format constraint (trading card anatomy: character, stats, abilities, frame) comes before stylization, so every design decision students make is working toward a known destination.</p>
      <p>This is the first unit where students are working in full color. The three-photo constraint from Unit 1 continues here, applied to reference gathering for the hero portrait. Students should finish the unit with a completed card and a felt understanding of how color relationships work — not just the vocabulary for them.</p>
      <div class="note-box">
        <div class="note-box-label">Structural Principle</div>
        <p><strong>Format before stylization.</strong> Students learn what a trading card looks like — its compositional anatomy, its stats structure, its character-as-focal-point rule — before they start making stylization decisions. This prevents the common problem of students drawing a portrait and then trying to retrofit trading card elements around it. The destination is established first; the journey is more purposeful.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section" id="questions">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Essential Questions</div>
      <div class="section-title">Questions That Drive the Unit</div>
      <div class="eq-list">
        <div class="eq-item">Who do you come from?</div>
        <div class="eq-item">How do artists use color to communicate feeling, personality, and meaning — not just appearance?</div>
        <div class="eq-item">What decisions does a character designer make, and how do pose, expression, symbols, and composition work together?</div>
        <div class="eq-item">How does working within a format constraint change the way you make artistic decisions?</div>
        <div class="eq-item">How have different cultures developed distinct visual languages through color and pattern?</div>
      </div>
    </div>

